## Step 2: Recall the definition of $D_0$ and its relation to ionization energy
$D_0(\mathrm{H}_2)$ is the energy required to dissociate $\mathrm{H}_2$ into $2\mathrm{H}$, and $D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^{+})$ is the energy required to dissociate $\mathrm{H}_2^{+}$ into $\mathrm{H} + \mathrm{H}^{+}$.

## Step 3: Understand the process of calculating the first ionization energy of $\mathrm{H}_2$
The first ionization energy of $\mathrm{H}_2$ is the energy needed to remove an electron from $\mathrm{H}_2$, resulting in $\mathrm{H}_2^{+}$. This process can be related to the dissociation energies through a thermodynamic cycle.

## Step 4: Apply the thermodynamic cycle to relate $D_0$ values to the ionization energy of $\mathrm{H}_2$
The cycle involves: $\mathrm{H}_2 \rightarrow 2\mathrm{H}$ (energy $D_0(\mathrm{H}_2)$), $\mathrm{H}_2 \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_2^{+} + e^{-}$ (energy $IE(\mathrm{H}_2)$, the ionization energy we're trying to find), $\mathrm{H}_2^{+} \rightarrow \mathrm{H} + \mathrm{H}^{+}$ (energy $D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^{+})$), and $\mathrm{H} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}^{+} + e^{-}$ (energy $IE(\mathrm{H}) = 13.598 \mathrm{eV}$).

